Template: magnolia/setup-method
Type: select
Choices: Configure manually, Import from .env file
Default: Configure manually
Description: Installation setup method
 Choose how to configure magnolia.
 .
 "Configure manually" will ask a series of questions.
 .
 "Import from .env file" will copy an existing environment file directly.
 Useful for reinstalls or migrating from another server.

Template: magnolia/env-file-path
Type: string
Default:
Description: Path to existing .env file
 Enter the absolute path to an existing magnolia .env file to import.
 .
 The file will be copied to /etc/magnolia/magnolia.env.
 A SESSION_SECRET will be added automatically if one is not present.
 .
 Example: /home/deploy/magnolia.env

Template: magnolia/environment
Type: select
Choices: production, development
Default: production
Description: Application environment
 Choose the runtime environment for magnolia.
 .
 "production" enables stricter security settings and reduced logging.
 "development" enables verbose logging and relaxed settings.

Template: magnolia/database-url
Type: string
Default: sqlite:///var/lib/magnolia/magnolia.db
Description: Database connection URL
 Enter the database connection URL for magnolia.
 .
 For SQLite (default): sqlite:///var/lib/magnolia/magnolia.db
 For PostgreSQL: postgres://user:password@localhost/magnolia

Template: magnolia/server-host
Type: string
Default: 0.0.0.0
Description: Server bind address
 Enter the IP address the server should listen on.
 .
 Use 0.0.0.0 to listen on all interfaces (typical with a reverse proxy).
 Use 127.0.0.1 for local-only access.

Template: magnolia/server-port
Type: string
Default: 3000
Description: Server port
 Enter the port number for the web server.

Template: magnolia/base-url
Type: string
Default: http://localhost:3000
Description: Public base URL
 Enter the public URL where magnolia will be reachable.
 Used for absolute links in emails, redirects, and password-reset links.
 .
 Example: https://magnolia.example.com

Template: magnolia/web-origin
Type: string
Default: http://localhost:3000
Description: CORS allowed origin (WEB_ORIGIN)
 Enter the browser-facing origin that the server will accept requests from.
 This is the URL users actually type into their browser.
 .
 In most setups this is identical to BASE_URL. It may differ if your
 reverse proxy rewrites the scheme (e.g. BASE_URL is https but you
 proxy internally over http).
 .
 The server will panic on startup if this value is missing.
 .
 Example: https://magnolia.example.com

Template: magnolia/turn-enabled
Type: boolean
Default: false
Description: Enable embedded TURN server?
 A TURN server relays voice and video call traffic for users behind restrictive
 NAT or firewalls who cannot establish a direct peer-to-peer connection.
 .
 If you answer yes, you will be asked for the required TURN settings.
 You can enable TURN later by editing /etc/magnolia/magnolia.env.

Template: magnolia/turn-external-ip
Type: string
Default:
Description: TURN server external IP address
 Enter the public IP address where the TURN server will be reachable.
 This is the IP that remote clients will connect to for media relay.
 .
 Example: 203.0.113.42

Template: magnolia/turn-secret
Type: password
Default:
Description: TURN credential signing secret (SESSION_SECRET)
 Enter a random secret used to sign time-limited TURN credentials.
 This must be the same value on all servers sharing this TURN instance.
 .
 Leave blank to auto-generate a secure random value.

Template: magnolia/turn-listen-addr
Type: string
Default: 0.0.0.0:3478
Description: TURN server listen address
 Address and port the TURN server will bind to locally.
 Usually 0.0.0.0:3478 (all interfaces, standard TURN port).

Template: magnolia/turn-realm
Type: string
Default: magnolia
Description: TURN realm
 The realm string sent to TURN clients during authentication.
 The default value is fine for most setups.

Template: magnolia/local-port
Type: string
Default:
Description: Local-only port (LOCAL_PORT) — optional
 If set, the server opens a second listener on localhost bound to this port.
 Traffic through localhost never travels over the network so it is always
 secure without TLS, even when the public port is not using HTTPS.
 .
 Leave empty to disable the local-only listener.
 .
 Example: 3001

Template: magnolia/smtp-host
Type: string
Default:
Description: SMTP server hostname (optional)
 Enter the SMTP server hostname for outgoing emails.
 Leave empty to disable email sending.

Template: magnolia/smtp-port
Type: string
Default: 587
Description: SMTP server port
 587 for STARTTLS (recommended), 465 for implicit TLS, 25 for plain.

Template: magnolia/smtp-user
Type: string
Default:
Description: SMTP username (optional)
 Enter the username for SMTP authentication.
 Leave empty if your SMTP server does not require authentication.

Template: magnolia/smtp-password
Type: password
Default:
Description: SMTP password (optional)
 Enter the password for SMTP authentication.
 Leave empty if your SMTP server does not require authentication.

Template: magnolia/smtp-from
Type: string
Default:
Description: Sender email address (optional)
 Enter the email address shown as the sender for outgoing emails.
 Example: noreply@example.com

Template: magnolia/admin-email
Type: string
Default:
Description: Admin notification email (optional)
 Enter an email address for admin alerts (security events, errors).
 Leave empty to disable admin notifications.

Template: magnolia/initial-admin-email
Type: string
Default:
Description: Initial administrator account email
 Enter the email address for the first administrator account.
 This account will have full access to the admin panel.
 .
 Leave empty to skip — you can create an admin account later
 by running: magnolia-create-admin --email <email>

Template: magnolia/initial-admin-password
Type: password
Default:
Description: Initial administrator account password
 Enter a password for the first administrator account.
 .
 The password must be at least 12 characters, Uppercase+Lowercase, 1 number, 1 symbol (?!$...).

Template: magnolia/autostart
Type: boolean
Default: true
Description: Start Magnolia Server automatically at boot?
 If yes, the service will be enabled with systemd and start on every boot.
 .
 If no, the service will be installed but not enabled. Start it manually with:
   sudo systemctl start magnolia_server
 Enable autostart later with:
   sudo systemctl enable magnolia_server
